Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.51,0:00:04.85,Default,[ Music ]
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.35,0:00:06.35,Default,>> Stanford University.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.60,0:00:08.83,Default,>> Alright.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.83,0:00:13.75,Default,Well welcome to Lecture number\N9 of CS 193p, Fall of 2013/14.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.33,0:00:17.40,Default,Today I'm going to finish the\Nanimation demo that we started
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.40,0:00:19.91,Default,on Monday, and then the\Nlecture's going to be
Dialogue: 0,0:00:19.91,0:00:23.79,Default,about auto layout, which is a\Nreally cool system for making it
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.79,0:00:26.96,Default,so that your user interface cam\Nadapt to changing conditions.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.41,0:00:30.99,Default,And then I'll do a brief\Nauto layout demo at the end,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.99,0:00:32.80,Default,just so you can kind\Nof see it in action.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.93,0:00:35.62,Default,Seeing is believing,\Nespecially with auto layout.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.62,0:00:42.01,Default,So this demo, where we left\Noff is the blocks would come
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.01,0:00:44.53,Default,down due to gravity and they\Nwould collide at the bottom
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.53,0:00:46.07,Default,and they'd kind of\Nrun into each other,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.42,0:00:49.75,Default,and then when a bottom row\Nwas full they would all kind
Dialogue: 0,0:00:49.75,0:00:51.89,Default,of fly off into outer space.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.89,0:00:56.27,Default,And I think where we left off\Ntoo was they would stack up
Dialogue: 0,0:00:56.32,0:00:58.45,Default,and they weren't\Nflying off, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.45,0:01:00.27,Default,And so why weren't they\Nflying off at the end?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.27,0:01:02.48,Default,Well, part of the reason\Nthey weren't flying off was
Dialogue: 0,0:01:02.48,0:01:06.16,Default,because they were, those\Ntowers of blocks were so tippy,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.42,0:01:10.20,Default,they were kind of wiggling, they\Nwere never coming to rest, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.50,0:01:13.22,Default,So they were never, the\Nanimation was never stopping.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.33,0:01:15.47,Default,It was always continuing\Nto move them a little bit,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:15.80,0:01:17.53,Default,and so we're going\Nto start off our demo
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.74,0:01:23.39,Default,by making those stacks a little\Nmore solid, a little less tippy,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.70,0:01:26.31,Default,by making it so that\Nthe blocks can't rotate.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.57,0:01:28.32,Default,So since they can't\Nrotate, they'll sit on top
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.32,0:01:31.12,Default,of each other much nicer and\NI'm going to turn gravity back
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.12,0:01:34.21,Default,up to 1.0, I think I had\Ntyped in .9 at some point,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:34.58,0:01:36.91,Default,just as far as the demo, but\Nlet's crank it back up so
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.91,0:01:40.13,Default,that they will sit a little\Nbit so they don't float at all,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:40.13,0:01:42.69,Default,you know, so they sit down\Nstrongly on top of each other.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.17,0:01:47.00,Default,Then what I'm going to do is\Nuse an attachment behavior
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.20,0:01:50.90,Default,so as the block falls, we\Ncan grab onto it, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.33,0:01:54.89,Default,And then we can kind of\Nswing it around and pick
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.89,0:01:57.82,Default,which stack we want to drop\Nit in and then let it go.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.82,0:02:02.23,Default,And then the last thing I'm\Ngoing to do is we're going
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.23,0:02:07.23,Default,to use the action block of that\Nattachment behavior to animate
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.23,0:02:09.54,Default,that and show the\Nattachment, I'm just going
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.54,0:02:12.20,Default,to actually draw a\Nlittle line to show it.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.20,0:02:13.36,Default,So it's quite a bit\Nto show there.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.62,0:02:14.74,Default,I don't think we're\Ngoing to have time
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.74,0:02:18.24,Default,to do this collision delegate\Nthing, but I'll post the code
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.24,0:02:20.24,Default,for that so you can see\Nwhat that's all about.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.79,0:02:25.76,Default,Alright, so, let's get\Nback over to Xcode here
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.76,0:02:26.89,Default,and go back into drop it.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.89,0:02:36.28,Default,And, okay, so, remember that\Nwe moved all of the behavior
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.59,0:02:40.72,Default,of this thing out into its own\Nsubclass of UI dynamic behavior,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.72,0:02:42.02,Default,called drop it behavior.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.19,0:02:45.15,Default,Right over here, this\Nguy, and so that's
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.15,0:02:47.04,Default,where the gravity\Nand the collision is.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.04,0:02:48.35,Default,And so what I'm going\Nto do there is I'm going
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.44,0:02:51.37,Default,to add another behavior\Nto that customer behavior,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.79,0:02:55.15,Default,which lets us control things\Nlike whether the blocks rotate.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.33,0:02:58.64,Default,Okay? We can also control\Nfriction, resistance, density,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.64,0:02:59.74,Default,those kind of things in there.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:59.74,0:03:02.74,Default,The kind of behavior that is
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.74,0:03:07.93,Default,that controls those things\Nis called a UI dynamic item
Dialogue: 0,0:03:07.93,0:03:10.27,Default,behavior, because it's\Nspecifying the behavior
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.27,0:03:11.12,Default,of that item.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.44,0:03:15.73,Default,Okay? So we'll call\Nthat, maybe something
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.73,0:03:19.79,Default,like animation options,\Nor something like that,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.79,0:03:22.69,Default,you can call them\Nitem behaviors, some,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.95,0:03:26.10,Default,you might call them physical\Ncharacteristics almost,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.21,0:03:27.52,Default,but that's, we'll do that.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.52,0:03:31.44,Default,And let's go down here\Nand lazy instantiate that,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.44,0:03:35.33,Default,so dynamic behavior in\Nthe mission options.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.08,0:03:38.45,Default,If not animation options,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.83,0:03:43.87,Default,then mission option equals\NUI dynamic item behavior
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.87,0:03:44.47,Default,alloc init.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.77,0:03:48.84,Default,So I'm just allocating\Nthis thing and I'm going
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.84,0:03:52.52,Default,to allow rotation, no.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.84,0:03:56.28,Default,So I'm not going to allow\Nthese items to rotate.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.62,0:03:59.65,Default,Okay? So the blocks will\Nhave to stay as they bounce
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.65,0:04:03.13,Default,on each other and collide,\Nthey'll have to stay nonrotated.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.98,0:04:07.50,Default,Alright? And return\Nanimation options.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.50,0:04:09.06,Default,And, again, we can do\Nother things in here
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.06,0:04:12.28,Default,like dot friction equals\Ndot density equals whatever,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.28,0:04:13.14,Default,but we'll keep it simple.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.52,0:04:18.23,Default,I obviously want all\Nitems to be added also
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.23,0:04:22.47,Default,to this animation options\Nthing and we clearly want
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.47,0:04:28.14,Default,to remove all items,\N[pause] as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:28.96,0:04:31.96,Default,And let's finally add\Nour child behavior.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.33,0:04:36.10,Default,Animation option, so the\Nanimation options act
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.10,0:04:38.18,Default,like any other behavior, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.57,0:04:42.35,Default,They just specify attributes\Ninstead of, you know,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.35,0:04:45.22,Default,applying the forces or whatever,\Nbut you can actually think
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.22,0:04:49.14,Default,of them somewhat as applying\Nforces too, it's just, you know,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.14,0:04:51.77,Default,like forces to keep them\Nfrom rotating or forces
Dialogue: 0,0:04:51.77,0:04:55.97,Default,to make them have higher\Nfriction, those kind of things.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.26,0:04:57.34,Default,Okay. Question?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.79,0:05:00.71,Default,[Inaudible background\Nquestion] What a great question.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.89,0:05:03.83,Default,You mean if, if you had\Nmultiple item behaviors
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.94,0:05:05.98,Default,that had different conflicting\Ndensities or whatever?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:06.60,0:05:08.06,Default,So that's a great question.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.26,0:05:11.03,Default,There are rules for that\Nif you have, you know,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:11.03,0:05:14.81,Default,a tree of behaviors and you had\Nsome item behaviors in there.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:15.00,0:05:16.51,Default,There are rules for\Nwhich one wins,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.51,0:05:17.97,Default,it's kind of the last one wins
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.97,0:05:21.92,Default,and how that's happens is all\Ndefined in the documentation
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.92,0:05:24.76,Default,for it, so if you're going to\Nbuild a tree so complicated
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.76,0:05:26.67,Default,that you have the\Nitems in there twice
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.67,0:05:28.96,Default,with two different behaviors\Nand different things, I mean,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.96,0:05:31.93,Default,that's pretty, I mean, if you're\Ndoing that, you really got
Dialogue: 0,0:05:31.93,0:05:33.85,Default,to know what you're doing\Nand so you really want
Dialogue: 0,0:05:33.85,0:05:34.67,Default,to read the documentation,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.67,0:05:37.55,Default,that would be considered\Nadvanced behavior
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.55,0:05:38.99,Default,to do that, but it can be done.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.19,0:05:39.81,Default,It is legal.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.73,0:05:43.48,Default,Okay. So, now we'll have that.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.48,0:05:48.52,Default,So now when we run this,\N[pause] we'll get a little less
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.62,0:05:50.91,Default,of the tippy stack thing,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.63,0:05:54.98,Default,although I didn't\Nchange the gravity,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.98,0:05:56.15,Default,but we'll see what happens here,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.15,0:05:57.83,Default,but you can see they're\Ndefinitely not twisting,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:57.83,0:05:58.48,Default,they're staying.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.58,0:06:01.33,Default,They still might bounce\Nslightly to the side if they,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.82,0:06:04.73,Default,for example, if I clicked\Ntoo fast they might crash
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.73,0:06:06.03,Default,into each other on the way down,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.75,0:06:08.51,Default,ones that are in\Nthe same column.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.51,0:06:09.11,Default,So here we go.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.11,0:06:10.52,Default,So now, they're going
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.52,0:06:13.06,Default,to be flying away a\Nlittle more reliably.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.71,0:06:15.46,Default,Let's try going really fast,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.46,0:06:18.39,Default,see if we can get\Nthem to tip a little.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.48,0:06:22.07,Default,Now I, if I have multiple rows,\Nthey should all go together.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.51,0:06:24.31,Default,Notice also I'm starting\Nto get a lot of blocks
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.31,0:06:26.88,Default,and it's the performance that's\Nstarting to get a little jerky.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.24,0:06:29.89,Default,Okay? And that's something\Nyou have to understand
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.17,0:06:31.37,Default,with animation, if\Nyou have a lot
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.37,0:06:33.03,Default,of things animated,\Nit's not free.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.19,0:06:34.74,Default,Okay? Animation is not free.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.74,0:06:37.06,Default,And if you had an\Napplication like this
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.06,0:06:39.40,Default,where you were dropping these\Nblocks and you allowed the user
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.40,0:06:40.66,Default,to drop a lot of\Nthem, you might have
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.66,0:06:43.09,Default,to start doing some other\Nthings, like, for example,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.09,0:06:46.26,Default,instead of having the\Ncollision boundary,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.26,0:06:48.55,Default,instead of having all the\Nitems collide with each other,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.74,0:06:51.95,Default,what if you just drew a\Nboundary around the top
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.63,0:06:55.14,Default,that they top ones\Ncould collide to.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.40,0:06:57.64,Default,You see? Then you would keep all\Nthose bottom ones from having
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.64,0:07:00.29,Default,to calculate where they're going\Nto go, because you'll notice
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.29,0:07:02.55,Default,that after they get tamped down\Na little bit, they don't bounce
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.55,0:07:04.49,Default,so much at the bottom\Nanyways, so you could take away
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.49,0:07:06.25,Default,that bounce and put a boundary,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:06.32,0:07:07.94,Default,because your boundary\Nis a UI DesiPath,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.94,0:07:09.28,Default,it can be anything you want.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.66,0:07:12.39,Default,Okay? So you have to think\Nabout that only, you know,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.39,0:07:14.74,Default,when you start getting\Nto extreme cases there.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.71,0:07:16.40,Default,Okay everyone.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.68,0:07:17.24,Default,Cool with that?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.91,0:07:18.39,Default,Make sense?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.76,0:07:20.24,Default,Alright, so, the last\Nthing we're going
Dialogue: 0,0:07:20.24,0:07:22.03,Default,to do is this attachment\Nbehavior.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.03,0:07:26.48,Default,So this is just attaching that\Nbar, which can be a springy bar
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.48,0:07:29.11,Default,or an iron bar, I'm going to\Nleave mine be an iron bar,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.11,0:07:34.26,Default,you know, a bar that\Ndoesn't collapse and expand.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.26,0:07:39.00,Default,And, we will use that bar to\Ngrab onto one that's coming
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.00,0:07:40.75,Default,down so I can swing it\Ninto the right column,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.75,0:07:42.47,Default,because right now it's just\Nwhatever column it comes
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.47,0:07:44.70,Default,down in, that's the\Ncolumn it goes in
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.70,0:07:48.29,Default,and that's a little bit\Nrestrictive, it makes it hard
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.29,0:07:51.72,Default,for my game to play\Nvery, very competitively.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.28,0:07:55.29,Default,And so, what we're going to do\Nto do this, we need a couple
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.29,0:07:57.36,Default,of things here, in\Nour view controller.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.36,0:08:00.76,Default,One is we're going to clearly\Nneed an attachment behavior,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.76,0:08:03.96,Default,so I'm going to create a\Nnew UI Attachment behavior.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.96,0:08:07.17,Default,I'm just going to call\Nit attachment, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.68,0:08:14.95,Default,And, I'm also going to need to\Nknow which view is dropping.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.22,0:08:18.66,Default,Okay? The view that's\Ncurrently falling
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.66,0:08:19.84,Default,down because that's the\None I'm going to grab on.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.84,0:08:23.11,Default,Because there's a whole bunch\Nof views in my game, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.11,0:08:25.55,Default,Tons of them, all of them are\Nstacked up there, which one,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.64,0:08:28.05,Default,when I start grabbing,\Nam I going to grab onto?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.05,0:08:29.62,Default,It's going to be the dropping\Nview, so I'm going to have
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.65,0:08:32.27,Default,to keep track of the\Ndropping view and, in fact,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.27,0:08:34.12,Default,that's easy to keep\Ntrack of, I'll just write
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.12,0:08:35.76,Default,down here every time\NI drop a new one,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.02,0:08:39.84,Default,I'm going to say the dropping\Nview equals the drop view.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.15,0:08:41.92,Default,Okay? So every time\Na new one comes down,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.01,0:08:43.52,Default,it's going to become the\None that gets grabbed.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.71,0:08:45.91,Default,So if I have multiple of\Nthem coming down at once,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.99,0:08:47.91,Default,it's the last one that\Nstarted coming down is going
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.91,0:08:49.02,Default,to be the one that gets grabbed,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.11,0:08:50.74,Default,if I grab onto it\Nwith this attachment.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.26,0:08:53.25,Default,Okay? So now I have\Nthe dropping view.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.96,0:08:58.29,Default,So, I'm going to do the\Nattachment with a pan gesture.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.46,0:09:00.83,Default,Okay? So we're going to see\Nanother gesture recognizer here,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.16,0:09:04.90,Default,because I'm going to grab it\Nand then as I move my finger
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.90,0:09:06.60,Default,around on the screen, I'm going
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.60,0:09:09.39,Default,to keep the attachment\Nattached to my finger.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.80,0:09:12.06,Default,So the block that's\Nbeing grabbed
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.06,0:09:13.44,Default,onto with the [inaudible],\Nit will kind
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.44,0:09:15.52,Default,of follow my finger\Naround, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.58,0:09:17.78,Default,With the bar behind it.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.16,0:09:19.39,Default,So, that'll be kind of fun.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.96,0:09:20.79,Default,So let's do that.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.02,0:09:23.23,Default,So you'll remember the\Ngestures we set up, right,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:23.23,0:09:25.43,Default,from our storyboard, right,\Nhere's the storyboard.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.74,0:09:29.70,Default,I'm going to go over and grab\Na gesture, it's a pan gesture,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.07,0:09:32.73,Default,which means follow the finger\Naround, so here's a pan gesture.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.73,0:09:34.52,Default,Drag this out, I'm just\Ngoing to drag it on top
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.52,0:09:36.75,Default,of my game view,\Nright on top here.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.02,0:09:39.99,Default,Here's my tap gesture, here's\Nmy pan gesture, so I'm going
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.99,0:09:42.42,Default,to drag it out, I'm\Ngoing to put it down near
Dialogue: 0,0:09:42.96,0:09:44.54,Default,where my tap gesture is.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.54,0:09:46.08,Default,Here's my tap gesture\Nright here, so I'm going
Dialogue: 0,0:09:46.08,0:09:48.36,Default,to put my pan gesture\Nright next to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.36,0:09:49.75,Default,I'm going to call it pan,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.75,0:09:53.14,Default,I'm probably teaching a bad\Nstyle here to call these pan
Dialogue: 0,0:09:53.18,0:09:54.50,Default,and tap, I call them that so
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.50,0:09:56.14,Default,that when you see them\Nyou realize, oh yeah,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.14,0:09:58.12,Default,that's the pan gesture\Nhandler, but again,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.12,0:10:00.28,Default,this could be something\Nlike grab drop,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.57,0:10:03.43,Default,that might be a better\Nname for this than pan.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:03.59,0:10:03.96,Default,Okay?
