Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.72,0:23:18.08,Default,Okay, now we drop one, we\Ngot it, drop another one,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:18.08,0:23:21.12,Default,another one, grab onto\Nthe side, another one,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.93,0:23:23.48,Default,try and swing it around.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.21,0:23:26.50,Default,Okay, if we swing it around\Nand smash it in there,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.50,0:23:27.45,Default,they'll still collide.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.86,0:23:31.43,Default,Okay? These are still\Ncollision, still happening,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:32.19,0:23:34.56,Default,and you can see also that\Nour game has a little bit
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.56,0:23:37.41,Default,of a problem right now, by\Nthe way, this not being able
Dialogue: 0,0:23:37.41,0:23:39.71,Default,to rotate is why it\Ndidn't tip off there.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.12,0:23:42.38,Default,Okay? Because it kind\Nof got, with being,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.38,0:23:48.36,Default,some item behavior is keeping\Nit from tipping off, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:48.36,0:23:51.09,Default,So, this is, by a bad far, game,\Nbecause how are we ever going
Dialogue: 0,0:23:51.09,0:23:52.72,Default,to line these blocks\Nup here, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:53.14,0:23:54.97,Default,So the next thing\Nwe would want to do,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:54.97,0:23:58.85,Default,and this is what I'm not going\Nto do because time here is
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.90,0:24:01.47,Default,in the collisions, okay,\Nwhen collisions happen,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:01.67,0:24:03.39,Default,collisions have a\Ndelegate, as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.99,0:24:06.59,Default,And in that delegate, what\Ncould you do is every time,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:06.87,0:24:09.52,Default,and the collision delegate tells\Nyou when a collision starts
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.56,0:24:12.01,Default,and when the collision\Nis ended being processed.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.50,0:24:16.39,Default,Okay? And in that ending\Nhandler, the ending message
Dialogue: 0,0:24:16.39,0:24:19.82,Default,that gets sent by the collision\Nto this collision delegate,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.82,0:24:22.45,Default,in that ending thing, you\Nwould then grid the thing up.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:23.13,0:24:25.48,Default,Probably look at its linear\Nvelocity, if it's moving
Dialogue: 0,0:24:25.48,0:24:26.48,Default,to the right, move it
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.48,0:24:28.32,Default,to the right a little\Nmore until it lines up.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:28.45,0:24:29.60,Default,If it's moving to the left,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.60,0:24:31.34,Default,move it to the left a little\Nmore until it lines up.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.62,0:24:34.46,Default,See? So, not too\Nmany lines of code,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:34.46,0:24:37.51,Default,but I want to make sure\Nwe cover auto layout today
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.51,0:24:40.80,Default,so we won't do it, but, any\Nquestions about what we did
Dialogue: 0,0:24:41.24,0:24:48.40,Default,so far or what we did here?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:49.52,0:24:50.45,Default,Okay. [Pause] Okay.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:50.90,0:24:55.44,Default,Alright, so let's get on to\Nthe lecture about auto layout.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:55.74,0:25:00.03,Default,Where is my [inaudible],\Nthere it is.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:01.34,0:25:03.47,Default,So what is auto layout?
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.22,0:25:07.17,Default,So auto layout is a way\Nof setting the frame
Dialogue: 0,0:25:07.51,0:25:09.43,Default,of all your views, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:25:09.43,0:25:14.06,Default,And these can be frames of views\Nthat you make in code or frames
Dialogue: 0,0:25:14.06,0:25:16.72,Default,that you drag out into\Nyour storyboard, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:25:16.72,0:25:18.34,Default,Although I'll warn\Nyou for your homework,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:18.53,0:25:22.51,Default,the frames of the cards\Nthat you make in code,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:22.51,0:25:24.91,Default,you're probably not going\Nto want to use auto layout
Dialogue: 0,0:25:25.03,0:25:27.01,Default,to lay those out, you're\Ngoing to want to use, like,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:27.06,0:25:29.49,Default,that grid class I gave you\Nor some class you write.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.57,0:25:32.14,Default,Okay? Because the rules for\Nlaying them out are kind
Dialogue: 0,0:25:32.14,0:25:34.38,Default,of beyond even what\Nauto layout can do.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:34.38,0:25:37.21,Default,Okay? So that's just\Na little hint there.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.52,0:25:40.66,Default,But all the other views, every\Nother, every single other view,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:40.66,0:25:42.94,Default,including the view that\Ncontains your cards,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:43.19,0:25:45.85,Default,you'll want to use\Nauto layout to decide
Dialogue: 0,0:25:46.17,0:25:47.35,Default,where it gets put on screen.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:47.55,0:25:48.47,Default,So we're going to decide
Dialogue: 0,0:25:48.47,0:25:52.58,Default,where to put these frames using\Nrules instead of using numbers,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:52.64,0:25:57.02,Default,instead of saying, putting it\N20, 20, 180 wide by 200 high,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:57.25,0:26:01.10,Default,we're going to use rules to\Ndecide where it goes, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:01.10,0:26:03.56,Default,And these rules are really\Nflexible and powerful,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.69,0:26:05.77,Default,and the rules are mostly\Nabout the relationship
Dialogue: 0,0:26:05.77,0:26:07.52,Default,between one view to another view
Dialogue: 0,0:26:07.52,0:26:09.56,Default,or between a view\Nto its super view.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:10.30,0:26:12.38,Default,Okay, now why do we want\Nto specify these frames
Dialogue: 0,0:26:12.38,0:26:13.96,Default,as rules instead of as numbers?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:14.27,0:26:16.67,Default,Because sometimes the\Nbounding rectangle
Dialogue: 0,0:26:16.67,0:26:19.08,Default,that contains all our\Nviews is changing.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:19.25,0:26:22.67,Default,Either because device\Nrotated, we're on a tall iPhone
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.67,0:26:25.20,Default,versus a short iPhone,\Nwe're embedded inside
Dialogue: 0,0:26:25.20,0:26:28.17,Default,of a navigation controller or\Nnot, we're in a tab view bar
Dialogue: 0,0:26:28.17,0:26:32.37,Default,or not, we're on an iPad in\Nsome popover controller view
Dialogue: 0,0:26:32.37,0:26:33.91,Default,or something like that,\Nthere's a lot of reasons
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.91,0:26:35.74,Default,that are bounds would\Nchange size,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:35.74,0:26:39.89,Default,so we want to build our\Nviews so that what's inside
Dialogue: 0,0:26:39.89,0:26:41.54,Default,of them adjust automatically.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:41.54,0:26:44.05,Default,Okay? And that's part of, a\Nbig part of your assignment,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:44.16,0:26:47.71,Default,although, your views want to,\Nin terms of your card view,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.71,0:26:49.95,Default,want to adjust automatically\Nanyway, because you're adding
Dialogue: 0,0:26:49.95,0:26:52.40,Default,and removing cards from them and\Nso they have to adjust anyway,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:52.40,0:26:55.61,Default,so you kind of get, probably get\Nthat for free, but all the rest
Dialogue: 0,0:26:55.61,0:26:58.52,Default,of your views, the one that says\Nredeal and score and all that,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:58.52,0:27:00.93,Default,you're going to want to use\Nauto layout to make those fit
Dialogue: 0,0:27:00.93,0:27:02.50,Default,in the right place when\Nyou rotate the phone.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:03.19,0:27:06.68,Default,Now, there, these rules, by the\Nway, we call them constraints,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:06.68,0:27:09.43,Default,layout constraints, so that,\Nwhen I use the constraints,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:09.43,0:27:10.19,Default,that's what I'm talking about.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:10.19,0:27:12.50,Default,The rules for how to set the\Nframes of all these views.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:12.89,0:27:16.78,Default,There's a really powerful API\Nin iOS for this, in other word,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:16.78,0:27:19.43,Default,a program interface with object\Nand its layout constrained
Dialogue: 0,0:27:19.43,0:27:23.53,Default,and all these mechanisms, but\Nreally, almost all of what we do
Dialogue: 0,0:27:23.53,0:27:26.05,Default,with auto layout, we\Ndo in Xcode, visually,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:26.36,0:27:28.67,Default,we don't usually go to the code.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:28.89,0:27:29.88,Default,If you're going to the code,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.88,0:27:32.24,Default,you're doing some pretty\Nadvanced layout, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:32.51,0:27:34.30,Default,I'm sure it's possible,\Nactually with the code,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:34.30,0:27:36.69,Default,you could lay your cards\Nout using auto layout,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.00,0:27:39.07,Default,but Xcode, probably not.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:39.07,0:27:42.60,Default,Okay? So since it's all Xcode\Nand it's all graphically,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:42.68,0:27:46.24,Default,I'm going to do this entire\Nlecture about auto layout
Dialogue: 0,0:27:46.24,0:27:47.94,Default,with screen shots, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:47.94,0:27:50.78,Default,And we'll just kind of walk\Nthrough it, I'm actually going
Dialogue: 0,0:27:50.78,0:27:52.12,Default,to skip these first few here
Dialogue: 0,0:27:52.12,0:27:53.41,Default,because I'll show\Nyou that in the demo.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:54.01,0:27:58.72,Default,So what I'm going to do it I'm\Ngoing to start with a view,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:58.72,0:28:01.47,Default,controller's view, right here,\Nwith a couple of things in it.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.54,0:28:04.17,Default,Thing one and thing two,\Nwith apologies to Dr. Seuss,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:04.50,0:28:07.19,Default,things one and thing two,\Nthey can be any kind of view,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:07.19,0:28:09.69,Default,they're UI labels in this case,\Nbut they could be buttons,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:09.69,0:28:11.90,Default,they could be custom views,\Nwhatever, they're just thing one
Dialogue: 0,0:28:11.90,0:28:16.49,Default,and thing two, and we want\Nthing one and thing two to be
Dialogue: 0,0:28:16.49,0:28:20.33,Default,in the right place when\Nthis bounds changes.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.33,0:28:24.40,Default,Okay? So what happens right now,\Nif we go and try and show this
Dialogue: 0,0:28:24.40,0:28:28.81,Default,in landscape, well, I could run\Nthis and then flip the simulator
Dialogue: 0,0:28:28.98,0:28:31.59,Default,to landscape to see, but\Nit's actually possible
Dialogue: 0,0:28:31.59,0:28:33.41,Default,to take your view\Ncontroller seen,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:33.72,0:28:37.31,Default,and flip it to landscape\Nin Xcode, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:28:37.31,0:28:38.77,Default,Now there are two ways to do,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:38.77,0:28:41.06,Default,one is Xcode actually\Nhas a previewer,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.28,0:28:43.51,Default,a previewer that will preview\Nwhat your UI's going to look
Dialogue: 0,0:28:43.51,0:28:46.80,Default,like on different\Nrotations, different iPhones,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:46.84,0:28:48.82,Default,even between iOS 7 and iOS 6,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:48.82,0:28:51.53,Default,if you're writing an app\Nthat's compatible for both.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:51.77,0:28:55.21,Default,But another way to do it is\Njust to inspect your controller,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:55.21,0:28:57.64,Default,so here I've selected\Nmy controller, right,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:57.64,0:29:00.13,Default,it's got a blue boundary\Naround it and I've selected it,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:00.33,0:29:02.60,Default,and I went to the\Nattributes inspector, you see?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:02.67,0:29:03.47,Default,Upper right there.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:03.59,0:29:04.46,Default,And I'm inspecting it.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:04.46,0:29:06.64,Default,And if you look at the\Ninspector for controller,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:06.64,0:29:10.53,Default,the top five things there\Nare called simulated metrics.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:11.03,0:29:13.78,Default,And this is a way to\Nsimulate your user interface
Dialogue: 0,0:29:13.78,0:29:19.37,Default,in different orientations or\Nsizes or with tab bars or not,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:19.55,0:29:21.70,Default,so that you kind of make\Nsure your UI is working
Dialogue: 0,0:29:21.70,0:29:23.81,Default,with auto layout,\Nso we're going to go
Dialogue: 0,0:29:23.81,0:29:26.52,Default,and switch the orientation,\Nalright, so I'm picking
Dialogue: 0,0:29:26.52,0:29:29.56,Default,on this thing orientation, and\NI'm switching it to landscape.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:29.87,0:29:31.86,Default,And when I do that,\Nmy scene changes
Dialogue: 0,0:29:31.86,0:29:34.15,Default,to landscape and\NI lost thing two.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.56,0:29:36.00,Default,Okay? What happened\Nto thing two?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:36.00,0:29:38.71,Default,Well, thing two is actually\Nthere, I left it there,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:38.71,0:29:40.24,Default,it's kind of grayed\Nout, you see it?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:40.43,0:29:42.61,Default,But it's not on screen\Nbecause unfortunately
Dialogue: 0,0:29:42.61,0:29:46.72,Default,in landscape it doesn't go down\Nfar enough to reach thing two.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:47.41,0:29:49.34,Default,Okay? So I'm going\Nto switch back.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:49.34,0:29:51.84,Default,By the way, you notice\Nthat the orientation there,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:51.84,0:29:54.21,Default,there's portrait landscape\Nand there's also inferred.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:54.56,0:29:57.69,Default,Okay, for all of these things\Nwhere you change the bounds
Dialogue: 0,0:29:57.69,0:30:02.27,Default,of your scene, inferred means\Ninferred from what's going
Dialogue: 0,0:30:02.27,0:30:02.98,Default,on in your storyboard.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:03.72,0:30:06.39,Default,So if it's this is the\Nthing that makes a bar come
Dialogue: 0,0:30:06.39,0:30:09.46,Default,across the top if this scene\Nis in a navigation controller,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:09.64,0:30:10.68,Default,or a bar across the bottom
Dialogue: 0,0:30:10.68,0:30:12.79,Default,if this scene is a tab\Nbar controller, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:30:13.17,0:30:16.78,Default,Portrait is the default\Ninferred orientation,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:16.97,0:30:19.58,Default,so if you pick inferred,\Njust like you pick inferred
Dialogue: 0,0:30:19.58,0:30:21.79,Default,for the other things, it will\Ninfer that you mean portrait.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.08,0:30:24.40,Default,So whether you say\Nportrait landscape, portrait
Dialogue: 0,0:30:24.40,0:30:26.74,Default,or inferred are the\Nsame for orientation.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:27.43,0:30:28.65,Default,Landscape means landscape.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:29.05,0:30:31.25,Default,So let's go back to\Ninferred, or to portrait.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:31.57,0:30:32.76,Default,We get thing two back.
