Dialogue: 0,0:30:35.36,0:30:36.64,Default,it just wasn't on screen.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:36.75,0:30:41.30,Default,So, I want to put thing one\Nand thing two in better places.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:41.30,0:30:43.46,Default,They're kind of in random\Nplaces, I want to put them
Dialogue: 0,0:30:43.46,0:30:47.04,Default,in places where I can have a\Nrule that says where they are,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:47.23,0:30:49.24,Default,and then what I'm going to do\Nis I'm going to put thing one
Dialogue: 0,0:30:49.24,0:30:51.51,Default,in the upper left corner and\NI'm going to put thing two
Dialogue: 0,0:30:51.51,0:30:54.04,Default,in the lower right corner,\Nand I always want thing one
Dialogue: 0,0:30:54.04,0:30:55.59,Default,and thing two to stay\Nin those corners,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.76,0:30:57.45,Default,no matter where those\Ncorners move.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:57.82,0:31:00.98,Default,Okay? If those corners move\Nup in the landscape or down
Dialogue: 0,0:31:00.98,0:31:05.75,Default,because it's an iPhone, the tall\NiPhone, like an iPhone 5, or up,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:05.75,0:31:07.90,Default,or whatever, I want those things\Nto stick to their corners,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:07.90,0:31:10.03,Default,so the rules I want is\Nstick in the corners, okay,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:10.03,0:31:14.46,Default,I'm going to show you three ways\Nto set rules, over the course
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.46,0:31:15.55,Default,of this lecture,\Nthree different ways.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:15.85,0:31:18.27,Default,The first way, you have\Nalready been doing.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:18.83,0:31:21.16,Default,Unwittingly, well,\Nnot really unwittingly
Dialogue: 0,0:31:21.16,0:31:22.30,Default,because I've been\Ntelling you to do it,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:22.54,0:31:25.10,Default,which is to use those\Nblue guidelines, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.41,0:31:29.86,Default,When you drag things around and\Nyou let the blue guidelines snap
Dialogue: 0,0:31:30.13,0:31:31.18,Default,to certain locations,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:31.37,0:31:34.49,Default,you're basically telling\NXcode what you want.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:35.16,0:31:37.70,Default,So when I drag thing one up\Ninto this upper left-hand corner
Dialogue: 0,0:31:37.70,0:31:40.67,Default,and these two blue lines appear,\Nit's really telling Xcode, yeah,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:40.67,0:31:42.96,Default,I want it to be stuck to this\Nline and stuck to this line,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:42.96,0:31:44.31,Default,in other words, upper\Nleft there.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:44.66,0:31:46.48,Default,And same thing when I\Ndo that for thing two.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:46.48,0:31:48.39,Default,Okay? I'm kind of telling Xcode.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:48.94,0:31:52.42,Default,But if I drag these two things\Nthen, right, and then I switch
Dialogue: 0,0:31:52.42,0:31:55.19,Default,over to landscape again, I\Nstill don't get thing two.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:55.72,0:31:59.52,Default,Why not? Okay, I did the blue\Nlines, how come it doesn't work?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:59.99,0:32:03.89,Default,And the answer is, all the blue\Nlines are is telling Xcode what
Dialogue: 0,0:32:03.89,0:32:04.63,Default,you intend.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:04.91,0:32:08.41,Default,You still have to ask Xcode,\Nmake those rules for me,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:08.75,0:32:10.07,Default,make those constraints.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:10.43,0:32:13.89,Default,Okay? So let's go back to,\Nto the portrait orientation,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:13.89,0:32:17.26,Default,and the way you do that, is the\Nlittle buttons at the bottom,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:17.26,0:32:19.94,Default,you see these buttons\Nat the bottom, those,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:19.94,0:32:21.57,Default,here I'll click on one.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:22.06,0:32:24.79,Default,Those all have to do\Nwith auto layout, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:32:24.79,0:32:26.21,Default,And how you're going\Nto layout the view.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:26.21,0:32:28.52,Default,And this one, that looked\Nkind of like a Thai fighter,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:28.71,0:32:32.24,Default,a Star Wars Thai fighter\Nthere, that one is kind
Dialogue: 0,0:32:32.24,0:32:36.49,Default,of for resetting, clearing\Nconstraints for the entire view,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:36.76,0:32:39.74,Default,okay, or for a specific\Nview or number of views
Dialogue: 0,0:32:40.10,0:32:41.18,Default,that you have selected.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:41.76,0:32:44.06,Default,So the bottom part of this\Nmenu is the entire view,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:44.32,0:32:45.63,Default,the top part is the same things,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:45.63,0:32:47.76,Default,but for specific\Nclicked on views, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:32:47.80,0:32:50.06,Default,So, we'll go through\Na few of these things,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:50.06,0:32:55.35,Default,but a really cool one is reset\Nto suggested constraints, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:32:55.51,0:32:59.37,Default,Suggested constraints means\NXcode is going to suggest
Dialogue: 0,0:32:59.37,0:33:03.41,Default,to you the best constraints, the\Nbest rules, and it's only going
Dialogue: 0,0:33:03.41,0:33:06.55,Default,to be very good at that if\Nyou use the blue guidelines.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:06.55,0:33:07.88,Default,Because if you don't\Nuse the blue guidelines,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:07.88,0:33:09.13,Default,it doesn't really\Nknow what to suggest.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:09.13,0:33:10.49,Default,It'll suggest something,\Nbut it's not going
Dialogue: 0,0:33:10.49,0:33:11.39,Default,to be good as we'll see.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:11.94,0:33:13.60,Default,But in this case,\Nsince both thing one
Dialogue: 0,0:33:13.60,0:33:15.81,Default,and thing two clearly have\Nblue guidelines to say
Dialogue: 0,0:33:15.81,0:33:17.70,Default,where they want to\Nbe, when we do reset
Dialogue: 0,0:33:17.70,0:33:20.07,Default,to suggested constraints,\Nit's going to work.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:20.50,0:33:23.00,Default,Now, nothing appears\Nto happen, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:33:23.08,0:33:25.18,Default,I did reset suggest content\Nand nothing happened.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:25.60,0:33:28.68,Default,But something did happen, and\Nwe can see that by clicking
Dialogue: 0,0:33:28.68,0:33:32.76,Default,on thing one and going\Nover to the size inspector.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:32.94,0:33:35.42,Default,Okay, so in the inspector there,\NI've switched over to size,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:35.42,0:33:39.12,Default,that thing looks kind of like a\Nruler, and size inspector has,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:39.12,0:33:41.36,Default,you know, where the current\Nframe is and all that,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.36,0:33:43.71,Default,but at the bottom, do you see\Nwhere it says constraints?
Dialogue: 0,0:33:43.71,0:33:44.87,Default,And I have two constraints.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:45.13,0:33:47.28,Default,My leading space, okay,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:47.28,0:33:50.41,Default,the reason that says leading\Nspace instead of left space is
Dialogue: 0,0:33:50.41,0:33:54.69,Default,because some languages,\Nleading is on the right.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:55.35,0:33:58.38,Default,Okay? So Hebrew, a language\Nlike that, it's on the right
Dialogue: 0,0:33:58.54,0:34:01.59,Default,so you might want your entire\Nuser interface oriented towards
Dialogue: 0,0:34:01.79,0:34:04.46,Default,coming from the right, okay,\Ninstead of coming from the left,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:04.46,0:34:06.08,Default,because all your text is\Ngoing to be going that way,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:06.08,0:34:08.11,Default,so you might want all your user\Ninterface to flow from that way.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:08.11,0:34:12.14,Default,So anyway, so leading means\Nwhichever leading you're talking
Dialogue: 0,0:34:12.14,0:34:14.95,Default,about, and I want the\Nleading space to be tied
Dialogue: 0,0:34:14.95,0:34:17.32,Default,to my super-view, the\Nedge of my super view,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:17.60,0:34:21.99,Default,by some fixed amount, and\Nthat fixed amount is default.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:22.59,0:34:23.39,Default,Default. Okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:23.39,0:34:25.57,Default,It's not a magic number, its\Ndefault, it's by the system,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:25.57,0:34:27.68,Default,the system decides what\Nthat default amount is.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:28.12,0:34:30.19,Default,And then you can see my\Ntop space is also tied
Dialogue: 0,0:34:30.19,0:34:33.48,Default,to my super-view's top edge\Nwith the default space.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:34.03,0:34:37.23,Default,So those two constraints\Ndetermine exactly
Dialogue: 0,0:34:37.23,0:34:38.90,Default,where thing one's going to be.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:39.12,0:34:41.17,Default,Now what about thing one's size.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:41.98,0:34:43.57,Default,Okay? Is thing one always going
Dialogue: 0,0:34:43.57,0:34:45.29,Default,to be exactly the\Nwidth it is right now?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:45.58,0:34:49.51,Default,No. Thing one, like\Nall labels and buttons,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:49.98,0:34:52.40,Default,it has what's called\Nan intrinsic size.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:52.73,0:34:56.66,Default,Okay? That's the size that\Nits text demands that it be.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:56.66,0:34:57.85,Default,And that could change.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:57.85,0:35:01.86,Default,If you change the text in\Nthing one, it needs to be wider
Dialogue: 0,0:35:01.86,0:35:04.35,Default,or it could be shorter if you\Nchange it to something shorter.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:04.71,0:35:08.05,Default,And so, it will change its\Nsize as you change its text.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:08.21,0:35:11.34,Default,Okay? Because you haven't\Nput a constraint on its size.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:12.05,0:35:14.70,Default,If you put a constraint on its\Nsize, it would then be stuck
Dialogue: 0,0:35:14.73,0:35:16.18,Default,to that size and that is bad.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:16.39,0:35:18.96,Default,We do not put size\Nconstraints, generally,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:19.28,0:35:23.15,Default,on intrinsically sizable\Nitems like labels and buttons,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:23.15,0:35:24.87,Default,and I'm going to show you,\Nhopefully, if we have time
Dialogue: 0,0:35:24.87,0:35:28.42,Default,in the demo, why\Nthat's bad, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:35:28.67,0:35:30.49,Default,So anyway, thing one only\Nhas those two constraints,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:30.49,0:35:32.91,Default,but those two constraints\Ncompletely determine thing one's
Dialogue: 0,0:35:32.91,0:35:35.58,Default,location no matter what\Nthe super-view does.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:35.96,0:35:38.23,Default,Same thing with thing\Ntwo, bobbing space
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.38,0:35:39.64,Default,and the trailing space.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:40.22,0:35:42.20,Default,Okay? So now let's\Ngo look in landscape.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:42.20,0:35:44.03,Default,I'm going to switch over to\Nlandscape and see what happens.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:44.44,0:35:47.91,Default,And you can see, thing\Ntwo sticks to that corner,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:47.91,0:35:49.19,Default,kind of exactly what we want.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:50.15,0:35:53.02,Default,Alright? And that's because\Nthing two's position is totally
Dialogue: 0,0:35:53.02,0:35:55.61,Default,determined by those\Nrules now, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:35:55.61,0:35:58.52,Default,Okay, so let's go\Nback to portrait.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:58.95,0:36:02.01,Default,So, I'm going to put a\Nbad thing in there, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:02.01,0:36:05.50,Default,So this bad thing is going to\Nshow bad things that can happen,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:05.63,0:36:07.78,Default,and I tried to put bad\Nthing in the middle,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:07.95,0:36:09.79,Default,but I didn't use\Nthe blue guidelines.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:10.05,0:36:12.50,Default,That's actually difficult\Nto do, but I did.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:12.88,0:36:13.70,Default,Okay, I put a bad thing in.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:13.70,0:36:16.88,Default,Also, you know, this bad thing\Nsize, it's too big for itself,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:16.88,0:36:18.59,Default,it really doesn't\Nwant to be that big,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:18.59,0:36:21.47,Default,it could be a lot smaller if\Nit was just an intrinsic size.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:21.80,0:36:25.80,Default,So, I just dragged it out\Nand moved the sizing handles.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:25.80,0:36:29.53,Default,It has no constraints, because\NI just dragged it out, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:29.53,0:36:32.64,Default,See how its size inspector there\Nsays no constraints, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:32.64,0:36:33.54,Default,You have no constraints.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:33.98,0:36:37.39,Default,So, what happens if\NI try to ask Xcode,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:37.67,0:36:41.01,Default,please give me some suggested\Nconstraints for bad thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:41.10,0:36:42.78,Default,Remember, I didn't use\Nthe blue guidelines
Dialogue: 0,0:36:42.78,0:36:43.89,Default,when I dragged bad thing out.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:44.32,0:36:46.89,Default,And notice, also, I'm using\Nthe top half of that menu
Dialogue: 0,0:36:46.89,0:36:48.47,Default,which is just, just\Nfor bad thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.68,0:36:50.39,Default,Okay? I'm not resetting\Nthing one and thing two,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:50.39,0:36:53.22,Default,although I could reset thing\None and thing two all day long,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:53.22,0:36:55.93,Default,because there's always going to\Nreset to the proper constraints
Dialogue: 0,0:36:55.93,0:36:58.03,Default,because I'm using the\Nsuggested constraints for them.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:58.12,0:36:59.51,Default,But anyway, so I'm just going
Dialogue: 0,0:36:59.51,0:37:02.37,Default,to reset bad things\Nconstraints and, boom!
Dialogue: 0,0:37:02.37,0:37:06.36,Default,Xcode gives it the old college\Ntry, but it's hard, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:06.60,0:37:07.52,Default,And, in fact, look
Dialogue: 0,0:37:07.52,0:37:09.10,Default,at the constraints it\Ncame up with there.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:09.30,0:37:13.71,Default,Height equals 62, leading space\Nequals 89, trailing space 68,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:13.71,0:37:15.25,Default,in other words, these\Nare all magic numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:15.56,0:37:18.33,Default,Okay? This is horrible, these\Nare terrible constraints.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:18.43,0:37:21.38,Default,Constraints with magic\Nnumbers are almost always bad.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:21.75,0:37:23.29,Default,There's a few cases\Nwhere they're okay,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:23.57,0:37:26.05,Default,but it's almost always bad,\Nand, in fact, if I go and try
Dialogue: 0,0:37:26.05,0:37:27.11,Default,to switch to landscape,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:27.50,0:37:29.89,Default,all of those number stay\Nexactly the same, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.89,0:37:32.88,Default,It stays 198 pixels from\Nthe top, and whatever it was
Dialogue: 0,0:37:32.88,0:37:35.00,Default,from the left, it's\Ntotally not what I want.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:35.12,0:37:36.95,Default,Okay? I tried to put\Nbad thing in the middle.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:36.95,0:37:39.20,Default,I want it to stay in the\Nmiddle, that's not even close
Dialogue: 0,0:37:39.20,0:37:39.94,Default,to being in the middle.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:39.94,0:37:43.52,Default,So suggested constraints\Naren't going to work
Dialogue: 0,0:37:43.52,0:37:44.91,Default,if you don't use the\Nbig, blue guidelines
Dialogue: 0,0:37:44.91,0:37:46.39,Default,because it's not really\Nsure what you want.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:46.65,0:37:49.68,Default,Okay? So, so let's get\Nrid of these constraints.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:49.68,0:37:51.33,Default,I'm going to go back\Nto that same menu
Dialogue: 0,0:37:51.77,0:37:54.00,Default,and pick a different item,\Nwhich is clear constraints,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:54.00,0:37:55.24,Default,and that clears all\Nthe constraints,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:55.24,0:37:57.44,Default,and goes back to this thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:57.44,0:38:00.25,Default,Notice, by the way, all\Nthe constraints draw,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:00.25,0:38:01.49,Default,you see the blue bars?
Dialogue: 0,0:38:02.08,0:38:04.88,Default,See them? Every single\Nconstraint is drawn.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:04.88,0:38:07.34,Default,And not only does it draw those\Nconstraints, you can click
Dialogue: 0,0:38:07.34,0:38:08.65,Default,on them, and edit them.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:08.65,0:38:11.22,Default,A lot of the constraints have\Nattributes, which I'm not going
Dialogue: 0,0:38:11.22,0:38:13.05,Default,to have time to talk about\Ntoday, unfortunately,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:13.33,0:38:16.44,Default,but those constraints are\Nfirst-class objects inside
Dialogue: 0,0:38:16.49,0:38:18.60,Default,of your, your storyboard.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:19.23,0:38:21.96,Default,Alright. So we're going to\Nclear those out of there.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:21.96,0:38:24.50,Default,And let's put in some\Nconstraints in a different way.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:24.50,0:38:26.67,Default,So this is way number\Ntwo to add constraints.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:26.67,0:38:30.08,Default,And way number one was use blue\Nguidelines and say suggested.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:30.39,0:38:32.50,Default,That's way number one\Nto put constraints on.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:32.50,0:38:33.64,Default,Number two is you can use some
Dialogue: 0,0:38:33.64,0:38:34.97,Default,of these other buttons\Nat the bottom.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:35.23,0:38:37.87,Default,Like this particular button\Nhere for aligning things.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:38.26,0:38:40.49,Default,So if you look in this,\Nthere's a lot of choices of how
Dialogue: 0,0:38:40.49,0:38:43.08,Default,to align things, if I\Nselected multiple views,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:43.40,0:38:45.47,Default,then all of those things at\Nthe top, like leading edges,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:45.47,0:38:48.00,Default,trailing edges, top edges,\NI'd be able to pick those
Dialogue: 0,0:38:48.00,0:38:50.46,Default,and I could line up the\Nleading edges or trailing edges
Dialogue: 0,0:38:50.46,0:38:53.19,Default,or whatever, of views,\Nmake them line up.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:53.32,0:38:54.82,Default,Okay? It's just alignment\Nthings, just like if you're
Dialogue: 0,0:38:54.82,0:38:56.48,Default,in some drawing program\Nor something.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:57.27,0:39:00.86,Default,I'm going to pick the bottom\Ntwo, which lines this thing
Dialogue: 0,0:39:00.86,0:39:03.76,Default,up with the horizontal\Ncenter in the super-view.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:04.37,0:39:07.64,Default,So it's going to be centered in\Nmy super-view, both horizontally
Dialogue: 0,0:39:07.64,0:39:09.55,Default,and vertically, so I'm going\Nto add two constraints here,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:09.55,0:39:11.49,Default,one for horizontal,\None for vertical.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:11.73,0:39:13.67,Default,And I can also specify an\Noffset from the center,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:13.67,0:39:16.00,Default,that's what that zero is\Nright there that's selected,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:16.06,0:39:17.96,Default,but I'm going to have\Nthe exact in the center,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:17.96,0:39:18.79,Default,so I'm going to say zero.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:19.30,0:39:22.33,Default,And there's also update frames,\Nyou see the update frames
Dialogue: 0,0:39:22.33,0:39:23.16,Default,at the bottom there right
Dialogue: 0,0:39:23.16,0:39:24.89,Default,above where it says\Nadd two constraints.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:24.98,0:39:27.66,Default,That popup, you can\Ngo in there and say,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:27.94,0:39:31.28,Default,and when you add these\Nconstraints, move my view
Dialogue: 0,0:39:31.50,0:39:33.78,Default,to fit those constraints,\Nbut I'm not going to set
Dialogue: 0,0:39:33.78,0:39:35.01,Default,that because I want to\Nshow you what happens
Dialogue: 0,0:39:35.01,0:39:36.90,Default,if you don't do that, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:39:37.20,0:39:38.98,Default,So let's add these two\Nconstraints, horizontal
Dialogue: 0,0:39:38.98,0:39:39.78,Default,and vertical centering.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:40.27,0:39:41.25,Default,Okay. There they are.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:41.52,0:39:44.18,Default,You see them, align center X\Nto super-view, align center Y
Dialogue: 0,0:39:44.18,0:39:45.49,Default,to super-view, awesome.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:45.49,0:39:47.04,Default,You can see them, they're there.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:47.21,0:39:48.63,Default,Notice that they're yellow.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:49.19,0:39:51.78,Default,Okay, yellow is like\Na warning, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:39:52.34,0:39:53.31,Default,Yellow is not good.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:53.38,0:39:56.38,Default,Blue is good, yellow not\Nso good, red is really bad.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:56.73,0:39:58.57,Default,Okay? Sometimes your\Nconstraints will be red,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:58.57,0:39:59.48,Default,that's if they conflict.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:59.48,0:40:02.26,Default,Like you have two constraints\Nsitting, doing opposite things.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:02.85,0:40:04.70,Default,And we'll talk about\Nhow we resolve all this.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:05.24,0:40:06.40,Default,>> So it's yellow.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:06.40,0:40:08.13,Default,Also, if you look\Nreally closely,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:08.13,0:40:12.34,Default,you see there's a dashed box,\Nkind of right, it goes right
Dialogue: 0,0:40:12.34,0:40:16.66,Default,through the word bad over to the\Nthing, you see it right there,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.66,0:40:19.00,Default,dashed box inside\Nof the bigger box?
Dialogue: 0,0:40:19.32,0:40:22.71,Default,That dashed box, I don't know\Nhow well you can see that there,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:22.71,0:40:25.00,Default,yeah you can see it,\Nthat dashed box is
Dialogue: 0,0:40:25.00,0:40:27.59,Default,where you constraints\Nsay this thing should be.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:28.67,0:40:31.31,Default,Okay? In other words, if you\Njust looked at your constraints,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:31.45,0:40:32.55,Default,where should bad thing be?
Dialogue: 0,0:40:32.55,0:40:34.92,Default,Well it should be in\Nthat little dashed box,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:35.49,0:40:38.14,Default,but since we didn't click\Nthat thing at the bottom there
Dialogue: 0,0:40:38.14,0:40:39.67,Default,that said update my frame
Dialogue: 0,0:40:39.67,0:40:43.34,Default,to where my constraints\Nare it didn't do it.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:43.34,0:40:44.79,Default,So bad thing is still\Nwhere it was,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:44.79,0:40:46.21,Default,and that's why these are yellow.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:46.91,0:40:50.01,Default,Okay? How can I know why\Nmy constraints are yellow?
Dialogue: 0,0:40:50.15,0:40:52.98,Default,Well one place is that little\Ntriangle in the upper corner,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:52.98,0:40:56.02,Default,the normal triangle where you\Nwould look at any other warning
Dialogue: 0,0:40:56.02,0:40:58.26,Default,in your app, and you can\Nsee this as the frame
Dialogue: 0,0:40:58.31,0:41:00.92,Default,for bad thing will be\Ndifferent at run time.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:00.97,0:41:02.74,Default,That's because at run time\Nthe constraints are going
Dialogue: 0,0:41:02.74,0:41:03.96,Default,to be applied and\Nit's going to be moved
Dialogue: 0,0:41:03.96,0:41:05.24,Default,into that little dashed box.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:05.97,0:41:08.59,Default,Okay? Another place you\Ncan see these warnings,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:08.59,0:41:11.42,Default,if you're constraints are yellow\Nis in the document outline.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:11.65,0:41:14.20,Default,Now we have not had a chance to\Ntalk about the document outline
Dialogue: 0,0:41:14.34,0:41:17.57,Default,in this class, but there's not\Nreally a lot to say about except
Dialogue: 0,0:41:17.57,0:41:20.01,Default,for that it's really\Ngreat and what is it?
Dialogue: 0,0:41:20.01,0:41:22.50,Default,It's every single\Nobject in your storyboard
Dialogue: 0,0:41:22.50,0:41:24.83,Default,that matters in an outline form.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:25.57,0:41:28.88,Default,Okay? So that's all your\Nviews, all your gestures,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:29.10,0:41:32.29,Default,all your constraints,\Nthings like layout guides,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:32.29,0:41:34.24,Default,which we're really not\Ngetting a chance to talk about,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:34.52,0:41:36.51,Default,but has to do with auto\Nlayout system, as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:36.73,0:41:41.30,Default,Those are all listed in this\Noutline, and what's really cool,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:41.30,0:41:43.00,Default,is you can click\Non them to select.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:43.14,0:41:45.09,Default,Because sometimes your view's\Nvery crowded and it's hard
Dialogue: 0,0:41:45.09,0:41:48.03,Default,to click on the thing you want\Neven using the control shift
Dialogue: 0,0:41:48.38,0:41:49.58,Default,trick that I showed you,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:49.87,0:41:51.99,Default,and also you can\Ncontrol drag from them.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:52.59,0:41:54.65,Default,Okay? You can control\Ndrag from a gesture,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:54.65,0:41:55.81,Default,you control drag from a view.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:56.00,0:41:58.88,Default,It's a really great place to\Ncontrol drag things from, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:41:59.28,0:42:00.56,Default,That's pro-tip number one.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:00.99,0:42:03.08,Default,Drag, control drag\Nfrom document outline.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:03.66,0:42:06.76,Default,The document online, also,\Nwill show you all the problems
Dialogue: 0,0:42:06.76,0:42:10.06,Default,with your auto layout and\Nyou see the tiny, little,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:10.06,0:42:13.11,Default,yellow circle up there where\Nit says view controller scene
Dialogue: 0,0:42:13.11,0:42:14.48,Default,at the top of the document\Noutline and then there's
Dialogue: 0,0:42:14.48,0:42:17.00,Default,that little yellow circle, I'm\Ngoing to click on that circle,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:17.31,0:42:20.18,Default,and it's going to show me\Nall the auto layout problems
Dialogue: 0,0:42:20.44,0:42:22.78,Default,in this controller,\Nin this scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:23.45,0:42:27.19,Default,And you can see the bad thing,\Nit expects a certain frame
Dialogue: 0,0:42:27.27,0:42:28.92,Default,and the actual frame\Nis different.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:29.33,0:42:31.00,Default,And you see the little\Ntriangle there,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:31.00,0:42:34.89,Default,if I click on that\Ntriangle, it will offer me to,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:35.02,0:42:37.20,Default,offer to solve the\Nproblem for me.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:37.74,0:42:39.67,Default,Okay? Now, how can\NI solve the problem?
Dialogue: 0,0:42:39.67,0:42:41.21,Default,Well there's a number of ways\Nit could solve the problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:41.43,0:42:43.85,Default,It could change the\Nframe of bad thing
Dialogue: 0,0:42:44.05,0:42:47.01,Default,to be what the constraints say,\Nthat's what update frame is.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:47.01,0:42:51.42,Default,It could update the constraints\Ninstead of being the vertical
Dialogue: 0,0:42:51.42,0:42:53.60,Default,and horizontal center\Nthat I just sent it to,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:53.60,0:42:56.06,Default,it could set them back to being\Nsomething that would make,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:56.06,0:43:01.71,Default,you know, the bad things frame\Nwork, or it could try to set it
Dialogue: 0,0:43:01.71,0:43:03.03,Default,to the suggested constraints,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:03.03,0:43:04.33,Default,which we already\Nknow don't work.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:04.69,0:43:07.26,Default,So we definitely want\Nupdate frame in this case.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:07.26,0:43:09.20,Default,We know we like our constraints,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:09.20,0:43:10.89,Default,that's the horizontal,\Nvertical centering.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:11.42,0:43:12.40,Default,So we're going to pick that.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:12.40,0:43:14.55,Default,So I'm going to leave update\Nframe suggested and click
Dialogue: 0,0:43:14.55,0:43:17.10,Default,where it says fix misplacement,\Nand watch what's going
Dialogue: 0,0:43:17.10,0:43:17.93,Default,to happen to bad thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:18.70,0:43:22.57,Default,It moved. Okay, now,\Neverything is no longer yellow,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:22.78,0:43:24.53,Default,bad things frame has been set
Dialogue: 0,0:43:24.53,0:43:26.88,Default,to what the constraints\Ndemand of it.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:27.50,0:43:30.64,Default,Okay? And I just hit back to go\Nback to, in the document online.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:30.86,0:43:32.40,Default,So now let's go look\Nin landscape
Dialogue: 0,0:43:32.40,0:43:33.61,Default,and see what happens\Nto bad thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:33.85,0:43:34.73,Default,It stays centered.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:35.20,0:43:37.36,Default,Okay? Bad thing properly\Nstays centered,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:37.36,0:43:42.77,Default,because the only rules it has,\Nis for it to be in the center.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:43.07,0:43:44.45,Default,Okay? Alright, so back here.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:45.49,0:43:48.20,Default,Okay. You can also\Nclick on, I told you,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:48.20,0:43:49.95,Default,you could click on\Nthese constraints.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:49.95,0:43:51.95,Default,So here I clicked on the\Nvertical constraint there,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:51.95,0:43:53.88,Default,you can see, I just\Nclicked on it,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:53.88,0:43:56.28,Default,and you see how it's\Nkind of highlighted.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:56.49,0:43:59.58,Default,Also notice that the attribute\Ninspector started being an
Dialogue: 0,0:43:59.58,0:44:02.85,Default,inspector that's inspecting the\Ncenter X alignment constraint.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:03.28,0:44:05.23,Default,Okay? And there's a lot
Dialogue: 0,0:44:05.23,0:44:06.57,Default,of things you can set\Nabout constraints.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:06.57,0:44:07.88,Default,Notice there's a priority there,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:07.88,0:44:09.70,Default,because you might\Nhave two constraints
Dialogue: 0,0:44:09.70,0:44:12.47,Default,in a complicated layout,\Nonly complicated ones,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:12.74,0:44:14.87,Default,you might have conflicting\Nconstraints.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:15.09,0:44:17.20,Default,You want something to be\Nunderneath something else,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:17.20,0:44:19.65,Default,but you want it to try and be\Nin the middle of the screen,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:19.65,0:44:21.76,Default,but if the screen gets really\Nsmall, then you want it
Dialogue: 0,0:44:21.76,0:44:23.99,Default,to just move down out of\Nthe way of the thing on top,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:24.25,0:44:26.34,Default,those kind of conflicting\Nconstraints you can set
Dialogue: 0,0:44:26.34,0:44:27.97,Default,priorities, and say\Nwhich is more important?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:27.97,0:44:29.05,Default,Is it more important\Nto be in the middle
Dialogue: 0,0:44:29.05,0:44:31.16,Default,or is it more important to be\Nunderneath this other view?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:31.46,0:44:32.13,Default,You see what I'm saying?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:32.13,0:44:34.79,Default,So you can set your priorities\Nbetween zero and a thousand,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:34.79,0:44:37.96,Default,so you, up to thousand items\Ncould have varying priorities
Dialogue: 0,0:44:37.96,0:44:39.22,Default,and generally you're\Ngoing to only use two
Dialogue: 0,0:44:39.22,0:44:42.58,Default,or three different priorities in\Nyour application, but, anyway,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:42.71,0:44:43.45,Default,the other thing you can do
Dialogue: 0,0:44:43.45,0:44:45.76,Default,when you have this\Nselected is hit delete.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:45.84,0:44:48.01,Default,And that deletes\Nthat constraint.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:48.01,0:44:51.35,Default,And now you can see the bad\Nthing only has this center
Dialogue: 0,0:44:51.35,0:44:53.09,Default,Y constraint.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:53.09,0:44:57.58,Default,So it no longer specifies\Nwhere it is horizontally,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:57.96,0:45:00.76,Default,and that is really bad\Nand now if you look
Dialogue: 0,0:45:00.76,0:45:04.32,Default,at the document outline, I\Nnot only have a little dot
Dialogue: 0,0:45:04.32,0:45:05.49,Default,up there, but its red.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:06.01,0:45:09.07,Default,Okay? And if I had a\Nconstraint that was bad here,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:09.34,0:45:11.23,Default,the problem is I have\Na lack of constraint,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:11.23,0:45:12.97,Default,I don't have enough\Nconstraints to specify
Dialogue: 0,0:45:12.97,0:45:15.36,Default,where bad thing is\Nhorizontally, but if I had two
Dialogue: 0,0:45:15.36,0:45:16.76,Default,that conflicted,\Nthey would be red.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:17.45,0:45:17.75,Default,Okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:18.07,0:45:20.04,Default,The constraint, the lines\Non screen would be red
Dialogue: 0,0:45:20.04,0:45:21.43,Default,and I would have this\Nlittle red circle.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:21.43,0:45:24.29,Default,So let's click on that red\Ncircle in the document outline
Dialogue: 0,0:45:24.85,0:45:27.77,Default,and here it's saying\Nmissing constraints, okay,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:27.77,0:45:30.54,Default,bad thing needs constraints\Nfor X position,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:30.54,0:45:31.63,Default,it's saying, which it does.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:31.84,0:45:34.64,Default,Because how else is it going to\Nknow where to put X, bad thing,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:34.74,0:45:36.48,Default,there's nothing that says\Nwhere to put it because I took
Dialogue: 0,0:45:36.53,0:45:39.18,Default,that constraint that was telling\Nit to be in the middle away.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:39.26,0:45:41.80,Default,So let's click on that\Nred thing, and when we do,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:41.80,0:45:43.15,Default,it's going to offer to fix that.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:43.84,0:45:46.77,Default,And it says let me try and\Nadd a missing constraint,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:46.77,0:45:50.08,Default,and it's going to do the best\Nit can to add a constraint
Dialogue: 0,0:45:50.08,0:45:52.65,Default,or a number of constraints\Nto make it so that
Dialogue: 0,0:45:52.65,0:45:54.33,Default,at least there's not\Na missing constraint.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:54.33,0:45:57.41,Default,This might not be the constraint\Nyou want, but, you know,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:57.41,0:45:59.88,Default,it's probably going to be\Nmostly suggested constraints,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:00.10,0:46:02.65,Default,but it's going to be some kind\Nof constraint so that there,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:02.73,0:46:05.18,Default,so the position of this\Nthing, and its size,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:05.58,0:46:07.07,Default,are completely specified.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:07.52,0:46:10.64,Default,So, in this case, since we\Nalready blue guidelined this
Dialogue: 0,0:46:10.64,0:46:13.24,Default,thing to the midline, and we\Nknow it's exactly in the middle,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:13.49,0:46:15.45,Default,it, when we hit add\Nmissing constraints,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:15.56,0:46:16.76,Default,it's going to put\Nthat thing back.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:17.41,0:46:19.02,Default,Okay? Now it's not\Nputting it back
Dialogue: 0,0:46:19.02,0:46:21.40,Default,because it knows I deleted\Nit, it's just thinking ah,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:21.40,0:46:23.53,Default,that's the best constraint\Nthat goes here.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:23.94,0:46:26.29,Default,Because it knows this thing is\Ndead center, so it's like, hmm,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:26.59,0:46:28.24,Default,dead center thing, I'm\Nprobably going to do that.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:28.24,0:46:31.29,Default,So it's really smart about what\Nmissing constraints it will put
Dialogue: 0,0:46:31.29,0:46:31.62,Default,in there.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:31.83,0:46:33.55,Default,Mostly it's going to use\Nsuggested constraints,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:33.55,0:46:37.30,Default,but it's even smarter than\Njust the suggested system.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:37.30,0:46:39.61,Default,Okay? So now we have\Nno auto layout issues,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:39.61,0:46:42.14,Default,we're back to having bad\Nthing in a good spot.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:42.40,0:46:45.11,Default,Now what if I decided I don't\Nwant bad thing in the middle,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:45.11,0:46:46.63,Default,I want bad thing to\Nbe stacked on top
Dialogue: 0,0:46:46.63,0:46:47.64,Default,of thing two all the time?
Dialogue: 0,0:46:47.98,0:46:51.59,Default,So I just pick up bad\Nthing and drag it down,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:51.99,0:46:54.74,Default,I'll use the blue guidelines,\Nor not, but I'm using the,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:54.74,0:46:57.35,Default,I'm just going to drag it\Ndown there and I drop it.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:57.59,0:46:58.44,Default,And what happens?
Dialogue: 0,0:46:58.61,0:47:00.38,Default,Well, I get the yellow\Nguidelines again,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:00.38,0:47:03.64,Default,because bad thing, once\Nagain, is misplaced.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:04.01,0:47:06.94,Default,That's because when you drag\Nthings to new positions,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:07.09,0:47:08.87,Default,it does not change\Nthe constraints.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:09.46,0:47:10.67,Default,That's important to understand.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:10.67,0:47:12.23,Default,When you drag things\Nsomewhere new,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:12.47,0:47:13.65,Default,the constraints stay the same.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:13.65,0:47:16.56,Default,So bad things constraints\Nare still align center X
Dialogue: 0,0:47:16.56,0:47:17.66,Default,and align Y, you see?
Dialogue: 0,0:47:17.70,0:47:19.68,Default,See them right there?
Dialogue: 0,0:47:19.68,0:47:20.77,Default,And that's no good.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:20.77,0:47:22.91,Default,So, what can we do about that?
Dialogue: 0,0:47:22.91,0:47:25.44,Default,Well, we probably want to\Ndelete these constraints,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:25.44,0:47:27.51,Default,because they no longer\Napply, and I showed you how
Dialogue: 0,0:47:27.51,0:47:30.85,Default,to delete them by doing clear\Nconstraints, and I told you how
Dialogue: 0,0:47:30.85,0:47:32.78,Default,to delete them by clicking\Non them and hit delete.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:33.01,0:47:35.38,Default,Here's another way to delete\Nthem, you see the little cog,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:35.69,0:47:38.17,Default,right there, where it says align\Ncenter Y and align center X,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:38.17,0:47:39.79,Default,there's a little\Ncog, if you click
Dialogue: 0,0:47:39.79,0:47:42.56,Default,on that there's a little\Nmenu, you can edit it,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:42.56,0:47:45.25,Default,which is exactly the same\Nas attributes inspector
Dialogue: 0,0:47:45.25,0:47:46.99,Default,on it, or you can delete it.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:47.44,0:47:49.24,Default,So I'll delete that one\Nand I'll delete that one.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:49.24,0:47:51.49,Default,So now I got rid of those\Nconstraints, bad things back
Dialogue: 0,0:47:51.49,0:47:52.49,Default,to having no constraints.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:52.49,0:47:53.72,Default,I just did that because\NI wanted to show
Dialogue: 0,0:47:53.72,0:47:56.43,Default,that there's multiple\Nways to get at this thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:56.43,0:47:58.41,Default,You can also delete\Nthem by selecting them
Dialogue: 0,0:47:58.41,0:48:00.13,Default,in the document outline\Nand hitting delete.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:00.51,0:48:04.47,Default,Okay? So now I have bad\Nthing, but where it is there,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:04.47,0:48:06.00,Default,it's not tied to thing two.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:06.00,0:48:08.88,Default,If I were to go landscape\Nright now, it would not stick
Dialogue: 0,0:48:08.88,0:48:10.69,Default,with thing two because\Nthere's no constraint
Dialogue: 0,0:48:10.87,0:48:12.19,Default,that ties it to thing two.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:12.36,0:48:14.50,Default,Okay? So, let's put\Na constraint.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:14.66,0:48:17.46,Default,Here's way number three, okay,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:17.46,0:48:19.08,Default,do you remember what\Nways number one are?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:19.33,0:48:22.23,Default,Number one is blue guideline\Nsuggested constraint,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:22.23,0:48:23.59,Default,that's way number one, alright?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:24.48,0:48:25.72,Default,Everybody got that?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:25.72,0:48:28.17,Default,Number two is to use the little\Nmenu things at the bottom.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:28.43,0:48:30.30,Default,Click, bring up the\Nlittle thing, type in,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:30.30,0:48:32.92,Default,click horizontal, whatever,\Nclick the things that you want.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:33.26,0:48:37.50,Default,Way number three is to\Ncontrol drag, control drag,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:37.50,0:48:40.49,Default,just like you're making an\Noutlet, between two items
Dialogue: 0,0:48:40.49,0:48:43.80,Default,that you want to have some sort\Nof constrained relationship.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:44.13,0:48:47.64,Default,So I'm going to control drag\Nfrom bad thing to thing two.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:48.20,0:48:51.23,Default,Okay? And when I do, I get\Na little black box just
Dialogue: 0,0:48:51.23,0:48:52.42,Default,like if I was making an outlet,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:52.65,0:48:55.75,Default,but this time it's saying\Nwhat do you want to tie
Dialogue: 0,0:48:56.08,0:48:57.63,Default,between these two items?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:57.63,0:49:00.41,Default,What do you want to be\Nfixed between these two?
Dialogue: 0,0:49:00.74,0:49:04.66,Default,So, you can actually select\Nmultiple of these using shift,
Dialogue: 0,0:49:04.66,0:49:05.81,Default,that's what it says\Nat the bottom there,
